1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,520
In previous demos, we've built our model step by step,

2

00:00:03,520  -->  00:00:09,960
and now it's time to implement the training code and train our model to generate text.

3

00:00:09,960  -->  00:00:14,900
Most of the content in this particular demo won't be LM specific

4

00:00:14,900  -->  00:00:20,100
and will mostly be implementing the standard by Torch model training loop.

5

00:00:20,100  -->  00:00:24,340
First, to do this, we need to define a few high perameters for training.

6

00:00:24,340  -->  00:00:27,090
We set the batch size to 64,

7

00:00:27,090  -->  00:00:32,400
meaning that every training step will process 64 sequences at a time.

8

00:00:32,400  -->  00:00:38,060
We then specify that we will train our model for 5,000 iterations,

9

00:00:38,060  -->  00:00:42,040
and we will also evaluated every hundred iterations.

10

00:00:42,040  -->  00:00:43,900
In this demo for validation,

11

00:00:43,900  -->  00:00:46,980
we will try to generate some text and just

12

00:00:46,980  -->  00:00:51,120
see how the result improves from one iteration to the other.

13

00:00:51,120  -->  00:00:53,960
But later in one of the exercises,

14

00:00:53,960  -->  00:00:57,320
you will implement calculating the validation loss.

15

00:00:57,320  -->  00:01:01,540
Finally, we need to set the learning rate which controls how

16

00:01:01,540  -->  00:01:06,285
much to adjust the model parameters during every training step.

17

00:01:06,285  -->  00:01:08,815
Then we tokenize our text data,

18

00:01:08,815  -->  00:01:11,175
and convert it into token IDs.

19

00:01:11,175  -->  00:01:17,090
The encode method returns a one-dimensional tensor where every element is a token ID,

20

00:01:17,090  -->  00:01:20,150
and then we put this tensor on the selected device,

21

00:01:20,150  -->  00:01:22,750
which will be a GPU if we have one.

22

00:01:22,750  -->  00:01:24,770
Now, having a tokenized text,

23

00:01:24,770  -->  00:01:26,810
we create a data set for it.

24

00:01:26,810  -->  00:01:30,250
We then create a random sampler that will randomly

25

00:01:30,250  -->  00:01:33,990
select the training example from our dataset,

26

00:01:33,990  -->  00:01:37,490
and we specify the number of training examples,

27

00:01:37,490  -->  00:01:39,050
we want it to return.

28

00:01:39,050  -->  00:01:42,125
This number is a number of training iterations.

29

00:01:42,125  -->  00:01:44,520
Multiplied by the batch size.

30

00:01:44,520  -->  00:01:48,060
Now to iterate over selected training examples,

31

00:01:48,060  -->  00:01:49,840
we will create a data loader,

32

00:01:49,840  -->  00:01:53,980
and we will also specify the batch size and the random sampler to use.

33

00:01:53,980  -->  00:01:56,580
Next, we initialize the optimizer,

34

00:01:56,580  -->  00:02:00,150
which will update model parameters during training.

35

00:02:00,150  -->  00:02:02,140
Here we use Adam W,

36

00:02:02,140  -->  00:02:04,940
which means Adam with way decay,

37

00:02:04,940  -->  00:02:07,980
which usually gives better training results.

38

00:02:07,980  -->  00:02:11,070
We also provide the learning rate that we've selected.

39

00:02:11,070  -->  00:02:13,680
Finally, we need to implement the training loop.

40

00:02:13,680  -->  00:02:18,165
We first iterate over many batches using our data loader.

41

00:02:18,165  -->  00:02:22,170
For every iteration, we switch our model into the training mode,

42

00:02:22,170  -->  00:02:23,750
and then from this mini batch,

43

00:02:23,750  -->  00:02:26,090
we get the input and the targets.

44

00:02:26,090  -->  00:02:31,390
We then pass the inputs to the model and our model return logits.

45

00:02:31,390  -->  00:02:33,870
Using the logits and the targets,

46

00:02:33,870  -->  00:02:37,250
we then need to calculate loss for this step.

47

00:02:37,250  -->  00:02:39,610
But to do this, we'll first need to reshape

48

00:02:39,610  -->  00:02:43,910
the logits and targets to calculate cross entropy.

49

00:02:43,910  -->  00:02:45,670
Why do we need to reshape?

50

00:02:45,670  -->  00:02:48,490
This is because we need to convert our data into

51

00:02:48,490  -->  00:02:51,970
a shape that is expected by the cross entropy function.

52

00:02:51,970  -->  00:02:53,810
For the targets, what we will do,

53

00:02:53,810  -->  00:02:57,360
we will reshape it into a one-dimensional tensor.

54

00:02:57,360  -->  00:03:02,110
Where we combine targets for all batches into one vector,

55

00:03:02,110  -->  00:03:05,670
and every element is expected token ID.

56

00:03:05,670  -->  00:03:07,710
For inputs, we do the same,

57

00:03:07,710  -->  00:03:11,010
but every element will be a vector of loges,

58

00:03:11,010  -->  00:03:14,290
and every logit is a score that our model

59

00:03:14,290  -->  00:03:18,050
gives to a particular token ID from our vocabulary.

60

00:03:18,050  -->  00:03:23,330
Then the cross entry function looks at the logits and checks if the model

61

00:03:23,330  -->  00:03:28,745
is predicting the next token eight correctly for every position in every patch.

62

00:03:28,745  -->  00:03:30,990
Given this data, it computes a loss

63

00:03:30,990  -->  00:03:34,130
and using this loss with the compute back propagation,

64

00:03:34,130  -->  00:03:38,150
and we run our optimizer to update our models parameters.

65

00:03:38,150  -->  00:03:43,830
The final step in the training loop is we need to reset gradients before the next step,

66

00:03:43,830  -->  00:03:48,840
and this is because we don't want to add gradients from different steps.

67

00:03:48,840  -->  00:03:52,120
On the next step, we will have new inputs and targets,

68

00:03:52,120  -->  00:03:55,140
and we want to compute new gradient values.

69

00:03:55,140  -->  00:03:58,040
This particular parameter means that we are setting

70

00:03:58,040  -->  00:04:01,280
gradients to none to reduce memory usage.

71

00:04:01,280  -->  00:04:02,960
Finally, on every step,

72

00:04:02,960  -->  00:04:08,530
we also print the step number and the loss we've calculated during this step.

73

00:04:08,530  -->  00:04:13,140
Because this loss is a tensor to extract the number from it,

74

00:04:13,140  -->  00:04:15,520
we need to use the item method.

75

00:04:15,520  -->  00:04:18,260
Then every 100 iterations,

76

00:04:18,260  -->  00:04:21,480
we also want to see how our model training is going.

77

00:04:21,480  -->  00:04:26,140
For this, we generate output from our model using a simple prompt,

78

00:04:26,140  -->  00:04:28,705
which in this case, is just a new line.

79

00:04:28,705  -->  00:04:32,300
That's it, now let's start our model training, and for this,

80

00:04:32,300  -->  00:04:36,180
I'll simply rerun all sales in this notebook.

81

00:04:36,180  -->  00:04:39,740
As you can see, our model training was going for a few durations,

82

00:04:39,740  -->  00:04:43,120
and we already got the first output from our model,

83

00:04:43,120  -->  00:04:47,680
which is just a gibberish because it was just the first step in our training.

84

00:04:47,680  -->  00:04:49,140
But as you also can see,

85

00:04:49,140  -->  00:04:52,285
the loss is gradually decreasing.

86

00:04:52,285  -->  00:04:58,070
I've let this model to train for a few hundred iterations and let's see what we've got.

87

00:04:58,070  -->  00:05:01,610
First of all, we started with just generating rubbish,

88

00:05:01,610  -->  00:05:03,830
and then if we scroll down a bit,

89

00:05:03,830  -->  00:05:08,970
then it started to generate something similar to our input data,

90

00:05:08,970  -->  00:05:13,930
and it even added the name of a character that is pronouncing a certain line.

91

00:05:13,930  -->  00:05:17,565
But as you can see, the output still doesn't look like English.

92

00:05:17,565  -->  00:05:19,440
But the loss is decreasing,

93

00:05:19,440  -->  00:05:24,360
and if we look at another and if we scroll down a bit.

94

00:05:24,360  -->  00:05:28,020
Now it generates something that is a bit more similar to English,

95

00:05:28,020  -->  00:05:30,720
and it even got a few words correctly,

96

00:05:30,720  -->  00:05:33,040
which is actually a small achievement because

97

00:05:33,040  -->  00:05:36,185
these words are collected from individual tokens,

98

00:05:36,185  -->  00:05:37,620
so to generate these words,

99

00:05:37,620  -->  00:05:41,610
it needs to get a sequence of these token 80s correctly.

100

00:05:41,610  -->  00:05:45,340
If we scroll down, now it starts with the name of a character,

101

00:05:45,340  -->  00:05:47,540
and then some lines that it pronounced,

102

00:05:47,540  -->  00:05:53,615
and even a few more words it got correctly like four and the and so on.

103

00:05:53,615  -->  00:05:57,430
Now it managed to generate a whole phrase,

104

00:05:57,430  -->  00:05:59,150
starting with the name of a character,

105

00:05:59,150  -->  00:06:03,005
and this is a line this character pronounces.

106

00:06:03,005  -->  00:06:05,610
Then as you can see, the more we train it,

107

00:06:05,610  -->  00:06:07,590
the lower the loss gets.

108

00:06:07,590  -->  00:06:11,290
If we let to train for a few thousand more iterations,

109

00:06:11,290  -->  00:06:16,010
it will start generate text in the style of Shakespeare poems, and that's it.

110

00:06:16,010  -->  00:06:18,430
That's our whole GPD model that we've

111

00:06:18,430  -->  00:06:22,450
managed to implement in just a few hundred lines of code.
